Bovine anaplasmosis is an infectious, non-contagious disease caused by the 
rickettsial pathogen Anaplasma marginale (A. marginale). The organism has a 
global distribution and infects erythrocytes, resulting in anemia, jaundice, 
fever, abortions and death. Once infected, animals remain carriers for life. The 
carrier status provides immunity to clinical disease, but is problematic if 
